Roy Only (Don't print this part):				XLR8Since I decided to write an example program that demonstrates the command-after-command concept, the XLR8SET information does not tie-in as well.It is probably for the best, as MULTCMD is under my name and XLR8SET isa M. A. D. Software product.  I still try to distance myself fromM. A. D. If you still want to mention XLR8SET somewhere (for the RAM savingsif nothing else), you might want to use the following as a starting point andstick it in a spare corner somewhere.  I will certainly trust your judgementon handling this.------------------------------------------------------------------------------If you are using the XLR8er adapter and the Houde patches, you may be interested in a utility available from M. A. D. Software.  It dynamicallyapplies the patches to the system each time the system boots and locatesthe first available location in low memory to load them.  The modificationsXLR8SET applies are functionally identical to the Houde patches, but only use35 bytes of low memory, instead of the 125 bytes the Houde patches require.To be transparent, XLR8SET treats the remainder of the command line as asubsequent command.  This allows XLR8SET to be specified in the AUTO commandalong with the command that was already there.  For example, if your AUTO linewas DO = STARTUP/JCL, you can change it to XLR8SET DO = STARTUP/JCL andboth commands will be executed.XLR8SET is available for $10+$2 S&H from M. A. D. Software.See the Resource:Companies listing for the address.